  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="KT152-kilavi">varaivu nīṭṭittavaḻi āṟṟāḷākiya talaimakaḷ “nī āṟṟukiṉṟilai” eṉṟu neruṅkiya tōḻikkuc colliyatu.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">Uttered to the confidante who approached HER [with the words] “you don't have the strength”, when she didn't have strength [anymore] as [he] delayed marriage.</p>
          </div>


        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="KT152">
<l>                yāvatu maṟikilar kaḻaṟu vōrē</l>
<l>                tāyiṉ muṭṭai pōla vuṭkiṭantu</l>
<l>                cāyi ṉallatu piṟiteva ṉuṭaittō</l>
<l>                yāmaip pārppi ṉaṉṉa</l>
<l>                kāmaṅ kātalar kaiyaṟa viṭiṉē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg xml:lang="en">
                <l>Nothing do they know, those who grumble.</l>
                <l rend="indent">
                    <choice>
                        <seg>If the lover lets go of passion so that [we] are prostrate</seg>
                        <seg>When the lover lets action desist by desire</seg>
                    </choice>
                </l>
                <l rend="indent">
                    <choice>
                        <seg>like the young of the tortoise<note place="foot">This comparison is to be understood "asyndetically": SHE without HIS desire is like the abandoned young of the tortoise.</note>,</seg>
                        <seg>like [that] of the young one for the tortoise,</seg>
                    </choice>
                </l>
                <l>what else has it got than to<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">cāyiṉ allatu</term>: this is a very strange construction. Literally this can only be: "apart from when ... ". For the rendering given above which follows the traditional interpretation one would like to have parallels at least. (A parallel is KT 305.7 <term xml:lang="ta">viḷiyiṉ allatu</term>, but unfortunately that is just as uncertain.)</note> grow thin,<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">cāyiṉ</term>: <term xml:lang="ta">cāy-tal</term> is mostly "to emaciate", but also stronger "perish". Perhaps here the openness is intended: it is unclear whether SHE/the young one still have a chance of recovery.</note></l>
                <l rend="indent">having come to rest inside<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">uḷ kiṭantu</term>: a coordination is also possible: "... than to rest inside [and] emaciate/perish ...".</note> like an egg without mother?</l>



            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
